      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "To understand what Aristotle meant by \"accent\", one must know some things about the written Greek of his time. Today, in most printed Greek texts—including those of \"the philosopher\"—three accents are used to indicate pronunciation. In Aristotle's time, the accents were not a part of the written language, but were supplied by the reader's knowledge of spoken Greek, which is something that we lack today. For this reason, some words that were pronounced differently were spelled the same in classical Greek, that is, they were homographs―\"written the same\"―but not homophones―\"sound the same\". So, a written word could be ambiguous in a way that depended on how it was accented in speech.",
        "spans": [
          {
            "start": 39,
            "end": 45,
            "type": "em"
          },
          {
            "start": 189,
            "end": 196,
            "type": "em"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "It is clear, from what he wrote, that Aristotle was being thorough in including accent in his catalog of types of Ambiguity. It is less clear just how common Ambiguity of this type was in his day, or how often it led to fallacious reasoning.",
